(5) Whenever a court is proceeding out of its jurisdiction, or where an inferior court has jurisdiction but an appeal will not furnish an adequate remedy for redress from its judgment, a writ of prohibition may issue. Clark Co. v. Warner, 116 Ky. 801, 25 R. 857, 76 S. W. 823; McCann v. City, 23 R. 558, 63 S. W. 446.

(6) A writ of prohibition can only be directed to a judicial tribunal, and not to a legislative body, such as a city council. Patton v. Stephens, 14 Bush 324; Stack v. Com., 26 R. 343, 81 S. W. 917.

(7) After dismissing an appeal for want of jurisdiction, the circuit court properly refused a writ of prohibition against the enforcement of the judgment by the justice who rendered it. Olmstead v. Mason, 3 Bush 693.

(2a) The Court of Appeals issued a writ of prohibition against a judge of a circuit court other than the Franklin Circuit Court prohibiting him from enforcing an order that the Auditor of Public Accounts draw his warrant upon the State Treasurer for the amount of an allowance to a pauper idiot. Greene, Auditor, v. Wolf, 175 Ky. 58, 193 S. W. 1048.

(2b) Prohibition lies to prevent the exercise of judicial power under Ky. Stat., secs. 331d and 33le, if the county court has no jurisdiction in the matter. Cullins v. Williams, 156 Ky. 57, 160 S. W. 733.

(2c) A writ of prohibition was properly granted by the circuit court to prevent a county judge from assuming jurisdiction granted to the county judge under an unconstitutional act, to wit, the Act of 1914, Ky. Stat., 1077a. Kilbourn, Judge, v. Chapman, 163 Ky. 136, 173 S. W. 32.

(10) Writ may issue to prevent a judge whose office had been abolished from issuing execution. Morris v. Randall, 112 S. W. 856, 129 Ky. 720.

(11) City council may be prohibited from removing an officer. Thomas v. Thompson, 102 S. W. 849, 31 R. 475.

(12) Writ will not issue if applicant has an adequate remedy by appeal. White v. Kirby, 147 Ky. 496, 144 S. W. 369.

(13) Injunction. Court of Appeals will not issue injunction when it has been refused by circuit judge. City of Newport v. Veith, 144 Ky. 501, 139 S. W. 774.

